{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539714","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539714"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:45:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:45:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16696"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16696","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16696"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.2,0.53,0.1,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9387"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115065"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9387"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16696"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97073"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1803"},{"type":"tags","id":"2780"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"8797"},{"type":"tags","id":"8855"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22205"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37588"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115065"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 71-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of a watery right eye and mild irritation. He has noticed his lower eyelid appears to droop away from the eye.  The optometrist did not have any concerns on his last review six months ago after getting new frames for his reading glasses. He has osteoporosis, diabetes mellitus and takes alendronate and metformin. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The right lower eyelid is turned outward, exposing the palpebral conjunctiva. There is associated epiphora (excessive tearing) and mild conjunctival injection. The cornea appears healthy without signs of exposure keratopathy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical antibiotic ointment","Temporary tarsorrhaphy","Artificial tears and lubricating ointment","Immediate surgical repair","Botulinum toxin injection"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with typical features of involutional senile ectropion (atrophic), a condition commonly seen in elderly patients where the lower eyelid turns outward (everts). Senile ectropion is usually caused by age-related horizontal lid laxity and weakening of the lower lid retractors, leading to feelings of dryness of the eye. Ectropions may be also be caused by weakness of the orbiclaris oculi, a facial palsy, trauma, or scarring to the lower lid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArtificial tears and lubricating ointment\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial management for mild ectropion without significant corneal exposure. This conservative approach helps protect the ocular surface and relieves symptoms while monitoring for progression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical antibiotic ointment\u003C/strong\u003E would not address the underlying anatomical problem and is not indicated unless there is evidence of infection, which is not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBotulinum toxin injection\u003C/strong\u003E has no role in the management of ectropion. It is sometimes used in conditions involving muscle spasm or inappropriate muscle contraction, such as blepharospasm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate surgical repair\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated for severe cases with significant corneal exposure, keratopathy, or if conservative management fails. This is generally more than 6mm of anterior distraction to be considered severe lid laxity. This patient\u0027s presentation is mild with a healthy cornea, making surgery unnecessary at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETemporary tarsorrhaphy\u003C/strong\u003E, which involves suturing the eyelids partially together, would be overly aggressive for this presentation and is typically reserved for severe cases of corneal exposure or as a temporary measure in facial nerve paralysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERegular follow-up is important to monitor for progression of the condition or development of corneal complications. If symptoms persist or worsen despite conservative management, surgical correction (typically lateral tarsal strip procedure or horizontal lid shortening) may become necessary.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Involutional ectropion commonly affects elderly patients and is caused by horizontal lid laxity and weakening of the lower lid retractors.","Conservative management with lubricating eye drops and ointment is appropriate for mild ectropion without significant symptoms.","Surgical correction is indicated when there are persistent symptoms or risk of corneal exposure."],"references":["NSW Agency for Clinical Innovation. Eye Emergency Manual [Internet]. 3rd ed. Sydney: ACI; 2023. Available at: https://aci.health.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0013/155011/ACI-Eye-Emergency-Manual.pdf","Patel C, Supramaniam D. When the eyes are dry: An algorithm approach and management in general practice. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2021: 50 (6).  Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2021/june/when-the-eyes-are-dry"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97073"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16696"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97073"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-22T09:00:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-22T09:00:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9387"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115065"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}